Fig. 6 3D nitrogen-doped carbon supported non-precious metals electrocatalyst for oxygen reduction reaction Mohammad Etesami Conceptualization Formal analysis Funding acquisition Investigation Validation Writing - original draft Maryam Oroujzadeh Data curation Software Shahram Mehdipour-Ataei Supervision Writing - review & editing * Faculty of Science, Iran Polymer and Petrochemical Institute, Tehran, Iran Faculty of Science Iran Polymer and Petrochemical Institute Tehran Iran Faculty of Science, Iran Polymer and Petrochemical Institute, Tehran, Iran ⁎ Corresponding author. Graphical abstract Sluggish oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) is a rate-limiting step in some electrochemical devices such as fuel cells. Thus, the synthesis and development of high performance, inexpensive and durable catalysts for ORR is a necessity. Metallic nanostructures decorated heteroatoms-doped carbons have been recognized as excellent catalysts in energy applications. However, nitrogen-doped partially oxidized three-dimensional carbonaceous supports were seldom studied for ORR. Herein, the synthesis of low Fe-Co bimetallic contents deposited on three-dimensional (3D) activated carbon (AC) is reported as an efficient and cost-effective catalyst for ORR in alkaline electrolyte. In the present work, AC was thermally treated by direct heat in air at 430 °C to enhance its electrochemical activity through increasing structure deficiency. AC and nitrogen doped AC (N-AC) were used to synthesize Fe-Co/AC and Fe-Co/N-AC. In both Fe-Co/AC and Fe-Co/N-AC, low amounts of non-precious Fe and Co nanoparticles were deposited on carbonaceous substrates. The air oxidation process, for partially oxidation of carbon structure and catalyst post treatment, was used for introducing defects to the catalyst structure. The performance of synthesized samples was evaluated by ORR process in alkaline medium. Keywords Electrocatalyst Treatment Air oxidation Non-precious metals ORR 1 Introduction Today’s concerns regarding finding and developing renewable energy resources have encouraged researchers to explore high performance and low-cost catalysts for applications in electrochemical energy related devices. Electrochemical devices such as fuel cells and electrolyzers are denoted as efficient and eco-friendly systems that can reduce the demand for fossil fuels, and diminish global concerns about energy crisis. Electrocatalysts, as a main part of electrochemical devices, should be cost-effective, highly active, stable and durable in the electrochemical reactions. Carbon, as one of the most abundant elements and inexpensive materials, has received great attentions in recent years. Recent advances in synthesis, structural engineering and applications of carbon-based electrocatalysts indicate their importance in energy [1]. Although, Pt and Pt-based catalysts have shown great performances in devices such as fuel cells, their high cost, limited resources in nature, their unsatisfactory durability, and facile poisoning are of their drawbacks that encouraged scientists to explore other alternative catalysts. Pt-free electrocatalysts, noble metal free and metal-free catalysts have been studied in electrochemical reactions and have shown comparable results with Pt in reactions such as electrooxidation of alcohols, oxygen reduction reaction (ORR), oxygen evolution reaction (OER), and hydrogen evolution reaction (HER) [2–6]. Remarkable efforts have been conducted to increase the performance of carbon-based electrocatalysts via increasing porosity, generating specific structure or creating some defects in carbonaceous structures. Incorporating heteroatoms like nitrogen, sulfur and phosphorous into the catalyst structure is an efficient way to improve the electrocatalytic behavior of the catalysts [7–11]. Several theoretical and experimental attempts have been carried out to unveil the mechanism and active sites of catalysts in ORR process [12,13]. By doping different heteroatoms such as N in the carbonaceous structure, the electron density in some spots changes [14]. As reported previously, the higher electronegativity of N atoms (3.00) compared to C atoms (2.55) results in positive charge density on neighboring C atoms that facilitates oxygen adsorption on the electrocatalyst for ORR process [15]. Increasing the number of defects also makes more active sites available for reactions. A simple way to create holes and defects in carbon-based materials is to heat carbonaceous structure via controlled air oxidation. By applying direct heating, defect-rich areas on the surface of carbonaceous structures are formed by partially oxidation of carbon atoms into carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide gasses [16,17]. By introducing nitrogen to the defect-containing carbonaceous structures, nitrogen atoms incorporate in carbon structure. Not only the nitrogen content in carbon structures affects the electrocatalytic performance of catalysts but also several parameters such as porosity, surface area, etc. have impact on ORR process [18–20]. It has been reported that the graphitic and pyridinic N contents directly affect the ORR current density and onset potential, respectively [21]. As has been previously shown, oxygen containing functional groups and nitrogen heteroatoms doped in the carbonaceous electrocatalysts can play as anchoring spots for metal atoms in metal oxide particles [22,23]. Using low contents of metals (precious and non-precious) in catalysts to reduce the cost and increase the performance of catalysts has been introduced in electrocatalysis which shifts the quantities of catalysts from bulky size to nano-sized metals or even single atom electrocatalysts [24,25]. Mixed transition metal oxides are promising catalysts in energy applications. A general formula is AxB3-xO4 in which A and B are Fe, Zn, Co, Ni, etc. [26]. FeCo2O4 which is a combination of ferrite and cobaltite has been widely used as supercapacitors [27] and in lithium battery [28]. It has been also used as catalyst for ORR and OER [29] while CoFe2O4 has been reported to study HER [30]. Wu et al. [31] successfully synthesized N-doped onion like carbon loaded with bimetallic non-precious FeCo catalysts. The bimetallic CoFe(1:3)-N-C exhibited a good stability and durability with a four-electron transfer in ORR. Spherical FeCo2O4-holow graphene oxide was synthesized by a multistep procedure on silica spheres as the template. The 3D spherical catalyst showed an efficient performance towards ORR and OER in alkaline electrolyte [29]. Despite the advantages of various state-of-the-art carbonaceous materials, and using non-precious metallic catalysts, electrocatalysts still suffer from synthesis complexity and high metal contents, in which, all result in costly catalysts in large scale applications. In the present work, to produce a cost-effective catalyst, low amounts of Fe and Co were deposited on AC, as a three-dimensional inexpensive carbonaceous support (compared to CNTs and graphene in terms of either market price or synthesis procedure) and the performance of the synthesized electrocatalysts was evaluated towards ORR in alkaline solution. 2 Experimental 2.1 Chemicals Activated carbon (AC, 99.9 %, 950 m2 g−1), methanol, ethylene glycol, urea, Fe(NO3)3.9H2O and CoCl2 were purchased from Sigma-Aldrich. NH4OH (25–28 %) was obtained from Merck. All chemicals were used without further purification. Distilled water (DW) obtained from Milli Q instrument was used to prepare all solutions. 2.2 Catalysts preparation Firstly AC was divided into two parts; each part was heated at 430 °C in furnace for 3 h in air at a heating rate of 10 °C min−1 and AC430 was chosen for deposition purpose. To prepare Fe-Co/AC430, 1 mM Fe(NO3)3.9H2O and 2 mM CoCl2 were dissolved in 20 mL of ethylene glycol (solution 1). In a 100 mL round-bottom flask, 30 mg of AC was dispersed in 20 mL of ethylene glycol (solution 2) and sonicated for 1 h. the mixture was then stirred for another 1 h. Solution 1 was added to solution 2 and stirred for 1 h before reflux. The solution was stirred and refluxed for 3 h at 160–170 °C. The black precipitates were washed three times with DW and ethanol, then, dried at 50 °C for 24 h. To synthesize Fe-Co/N-AC430, firstly, N-AC430 was prepared by refluxing 200 mg of AC430 in 50 mL of ammonium hydroxide at 90 °C for 24 h. The nitrogen-doped AC (N-AC430) was washed and centrifuged several times at 5000 rpm with DW and ethanol. The N-AC430 was dried at 50 °C overnight. The N-AC430 was dispersed in 40 mL of DW-ethanol (1:1) and stirred for 1 h. Specific amounts of Fe(NO3)3.9H2O and CoCl2 were added to the above mixture (to achieve 1 mM and 2 mM of salts) and extra amount of urea (15 mM) was added to the mixture after 1 h. The solution was refluxed at 90 °C for 3 h. The black precipitates were washed several times in DW and ethanol and dried at 50 °C for 24 h in an oven. 2.3 Materials characterization A scanning electron microscope (SEM, Leo Supra 50 zvP) equipped with energy dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDX) was used to observe the morphology of the synthesized electrocatalysts. To characterize the structure of the electrocatalysts, a high resolution X-ray diffractometer (Jeol Jdx-8030) using Ni-filtered CuK α radiation (λ = 1.54056 Å) with scanning rate of 1.2° min−1 working at 40 kV and 40 mA with angular range of 5°- 70° was used. Thermal gravimetric analysis (TGA) was conducted by Polymer Lab TGA-1500 at a heating rate of 10 °C min−1 in air, starting from room temperature to 800 °C. Raman spectra were recorded by a Renishaw 1000 with a He-Ne laser (532 nm). Brunauer-Emmett-Teller (BET) method was used to measure the surface area of catalysts through nitrogen adsorption-desorption using Micromeritics, ASAP 2020 instrument. CHNS analysis was measured by Elementar Analysensysteme GmbH instrument. Metals quantities were measured by a PerkinElmer Optima 4300 DV ICP-OES through dissolving samples in nitric acid. For the electrochemical tests such as cyclic voltammetry (CV), linear sweep voltammetry (LSV), and chronoamperometry experiments an Ivium P/G stat (IVIUM technologies vertex, 100 mA/1A) was employed. 2.4 Electrochemical tests For the electrochemical tests, a dispersion solution of 1 mg mL−1 was used to disperse 20 μg of each catalysts. Before each test, 0.1 M KOH solutions were purged with N2 and O2 for at least 30 min. To run the electrochemical experiments, a three-electrode electrochemical cell with a glassy carbon electrode (GCE, 3 mm diameter) or rotating disk electrode (RDE, 3 mm diameter), a Pt wire (5 cm) and a calomel electrode (inner solution 3 M KCl) were used as working, counter and reference electrodes, respectively. 3 Results and discussion The synthetic procedures of 3D Fe-Co/N-AC and Fe-Co/AC are schematically illustrated in Fig. 1 . The AC was chosen as an inexpensive three-dimensional (3D) carbonaceous support. AC was heated at 430 °C in air to create various edges. Thermal gravimetric analysis (TGA) of AC was carried out in air (Fig. 2 a). AC exhibited a good thermal stability at low temperatures and less than 5 % of AC was oxidized at temperatures ca. 450–500 °C. At the temperatures above 500 °C, intense decomposition of AC was observed. Exposing carbonaceous materials to straight heat in presence of air or oxygen is of the most facile and inexpensive methods to oxidize carbonaceous structures. By exposing carbonaceous materials to high temperatures in air, the carbonaceous structure starts to partially oxidize in presence of oxygen. As reported, formation of carbonyl and hydroxyl functional groups occurs at layer edges. Besides, carbonaceous materials start to oxidize and create edges at high temperatures in air atmosphere. This process has been reported for carbon nanotubes (CNTs) [16] and graphene (G) [17] which are of 1D and 2D materials, respectively. By applying different temperatures at different expose time, the carbon atoms in carbonaceous structure are oxidized to carbon monoxide and carbon dioxide that results in new edges comprising functional groups in carbon structure. Various methods have been proposed to incorporate nitrogen atoms in carbonaceous structure. Heating materials in ammonia atmosphere [32], ultra-sonication of carbon-based materials in ammonia solution [33], and annealing carbonaceous material with nitrogen containing chemicals in an inert atmosphere [34] have been reported, however an easy way to dope high content of nitrogen is by thermal treatment of carbon structure in ammonia [12]. By mixing AC430 in ammonia and stirring at 90 °C for 24 h nitrogen incorporation was accomplished to achieve N-AC430. To reach the optimum nitrogen incorporation, annealed AC (AC430) was chosen to present more oxygen-containing active sites with negatively charged for adapting nitrogen sites. Nitrogen incorporation in AC was determined by CHN analyzer. The analysis showed the nitrogen/carbon ratio in N-AC sample was around 1.5 %. To determine the surface area of AC and N-AC, Brunauer-Emmett-Teller (BET) analysis was carried out. The surface areas were found to be 949.98 cm2 g−1 for AC and 997.63 cm2 g−1 for N-AC (Fig. 2b). New defects were formed in AC due to the partly gasification of carbonaceous structure when AC powder is exposed to air at high temperatures. Raman spectra of AC, AC430 and N-AC430 were recorded and ID and IG peaks were measured for samples. By calculating ID/IG ratio, the ID/IG ratios were found to be 0.94, 0.93 and 1.01 for AC, AC430 and N-AC430, respectively (Fig. 2c). The ID/IG ratio was slightly reduced after mild heat treatment which is because of graphitic crystallinity enhancement [17,35]. The values of ID/IG ratio indicated that applying temperature to AC resulted in formation of new edges, more surface area and active sites in oxidized AC. As it has been proved [16,36], by partially oxidation of carbonaceous materials, oxygen-containing functional groups such as carboxyl and carbonyl increases at newly oxidized edges which can act as reaction sites. N-AC430 and AC430 were further characterized by Raman spectroscopy. The D band peaks for both AC and N-AC were located at 1333.989 cm−1 while the G band appeared at 1602.212 cm−1 and 1597.057 cm−1 for AC and N-AC, respectively. The downshift of G band peak in N-AC430 compared to AC430 was due to partially filled orbitals in nitrogen atoms and its electron donation behavior in N-AC [37,38]. To deposit Fe and Co nanoparticles on AC430 and N-AC430 carbonaceous supports, two methods were employed to synthesize FeCo/AC and FeCo/ N-AC. Weak and noisy XRD peaks of FeCo such as (311) were detected which was due to the poor nanoparticles crystallinity [39] or very low metal contents. The broad (002) peak at 2θ = 24° indicated the presence of carbon in all samples (Fig. 2d). Also, the metal content of FeCo/ N-AC, determined by ICP-OES, was 1.13 at %Fe and 2.04 at %Co. Fig. 3 shows the FT-IR spectra of AC, N-AC and FeCo/N-AC. Most obvious changes were observed at oxygen- and nitrogen containing groups at 1150–1200 and 1500−1650 cm−1. FT-IR spectra confirmed that the N-AC and FeCo/N-AC structures were modified after nitrogen doping of AC by appearing out of plane bending NH group at about 1567 cm−1 and CN stretching vibration band at about 1192 cm−1. FESEM images of FeCo/N-AC and its related elemental mapping are shown in Fig. 4 (a–g). As it can be seen in this figure, C, N, Fe, Co and O elements were homogeneously distributed in the catalyst that indicates the uniform distribution of nitrogen doping, and Fe and Co nanoparticles deposition in carbonaceous substrate. EDS spectrum of the catalyst (Fig. 4h) confirmed the Fe and Co nanoparticles were successfully deposited on N-AC430. FeCo/N-AC indicated a porous structure that nanoparticles bellow 10 nm were formed on carbonaceous substrate. TEM images of the FeCo/N-AC (with two different scales) were shown in Fig. 4(i,j) which Fe-Co nanoparticles can be observed over the carbonaceous substrate. As reported previously, metal-O/N bonds form between carbonaceous support and metallic particles. Functional groups on carbon structures such as hydroxyl and carboxyl interact with metallic seeds by various types of van deer Waal’s forces, covalent and hydrogen bonds let the metal seeds grow on carbon structures [40]. Besides the catalytic performance of carbon structure, metallic nanoparticles improve the electrocatalytic performance. As a practical application, electrocatalytic performance of synthesized electrocatalysts was studied towards ORR in alkaline electrolyte. The cyclic voltammograms (CVs) of all catalysts were carried out in N2 and O2 saturated alkaline electrolytes where different activities were recorded. As an instance, the CVs of FeCo/N-AC430 sample in N2- and O2-saturated 0.1 M KOH are shown in Fig. 5 a. All potentials were converted to E RHE according to the following equation E RHE= E calomel+ 0.059 pH + 0.241. The FeCo/N-AC showed a good performance to ORR with an onset potential of ca. 0.9 V. For comparison, polarization curves of AC, AC430, N-AC, N-AC430, FeCo/AC430 and FeCo/N-AC430 were recorded by linear sweep voltammetry (LSV) and shown after subtraction of background currents (Fig. 5b). The performances of N doped samples towards ORR were improved compared to N-free samples, as can be seen for N-AC to AC and FeCo/N-AC to FeCo/AC. Using low content of non-precious metallic counterparts is a way to reduce the total cost of catalysts. Addition of low content of Fe and Co deposited on AC430 and N-AC430, exhibited catalysts improvement in ORR process compared to carbonaceous catalysts. It was also found that, amongst all catalysts, FeCo/N-AC430 exhibited better ORR performance in alkaline electrolyte. The active sites on metallic nanoparticles were not the only reactive sites for ORR but also functional groups tailored on AC and incorporated nitrogen in carbon structure provided reactive sites for electrocatalytic process [40]. In both cases, incorporation of nitrogen led to ORR enhancement in electrocatalysts as it was observed for FeCo/N-AC430 to FeCo/AC430 and N-AC to AC. Not only the performance of FeCo/N-AC430 was the highest amongst all catalysts by exhibiting higher peak potential but also its onset potential occurred in more positive potentials that indicated better electrocatalytic activities of FeCo/N-AC430. To further study the ORR process in alkaline electrolyte, this reaction was investigated on rotating disk electrode (RDE). The ORR on RDE was carried out at different disk rotations. The half-wave potential of FeCo/ N-AC was found to be ca. 20 mV compared to Pt/C. The results were also comparable with previous articles [29,41]. As reported [42], the ORR comprises two successive steps with the overall four-electron transfer, via the intermediate ( H O 2 - ) which can be dissociated to generate OH−. (1) O 2 + H 2 O + 2 e - ↔ H O 2 - + O H - E 0 = - 0.065 V / N H E (2) H O 2 - + H 2 O + 2 e - ↔ 3 O H - E 0 = 0.867 V / N H E (3) H O 2 - ↔ 1 2 O 2 + O H - The ORR process was also studied on FeCo/N-AC430 electrocatalyst by RDE at different disk rotation (Fig. 5c). As the disk rotation speed increases, the polarization curves changes according to Koutecky-Levich equation: 1 i = 1 i k + 1 i d = 1 n F k C O 2 + 1 B ω 1 / 2 B = 0.62 n F C O 2 D O 2 2 / 3 ʋ - 1 / 6 Where i, ik, id, n, ω and F are current density, kinetic and diffusion currents, number of transferred electrons, angular velocity and Faraday constant 96,495 C mol−1), respectively. ʋ (0.01 cm2 s−1), CO2 (1.21 × 10−6 mol cm−3), DO2 (1.85 × 10−5 cm2 s−1) are electrolyte kinetic viscosity, oxygen concentration in electrolyte, diffusion coefficient of O2. The number of electrons, calculated from the Koutecky-Levich equation was found to be ca. 4.02 from potential between 0.6 V to 0.3 V versus RHE (Fig. 5d) which was in a good agreement with the proposed reactions. The faster electron transfer and more positive onset potential was seen in the catalysts with doped nitrogen structure. It has been reported previously that nitrogen (pyridinic and graphitic) doped in carbonaceous structure improves the performance of carbon-based catalysts for ORR [43]. Fig. 6 a shows the durability test of FeCo/N-AC430 for ORR. As it is seen, small performance decay was monitored for ORR test after 1000 cycles. Long-term performance of the FeCo/N-AC430 was evaluated in O2-saturated 0.1 M KOH electrolyte. As it can be seen in Fig. 6b, chronoamperograms of FeCo/N-AC430 and Pt/C were carried out for a long period of 10,000 s. The larger current loss was monitored on Pt/C than FeCo/N-AC in which that the ORR current generated on FeCo/N-AC reached to ca. 70 % while on Pt/C decreased to ca. 40 % after 10,000 s. To observe the catalysts stability against alcohol penetration into the electrolyte, 2 M methanol was introduced to the O2-saturated alkaline solution after 150 s (Fig. 6c). A significant decay was observed in ORR currents on Pt/C catalyst whereas FeCo/N-AC exhibited a better performance towards ORR in presence of methanol poisoning. As it appeared from the data, the synthesized FeCo/N-AC was electrochemically more active than other samples to ORR in alkaline solution by presenting higher surface area, more defects and more reactive sites to the target molecules. 4 Conclusions Fe-Co/N-AC was synthesized as electrocatalyst to study oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) in alkaline electrolyte. Activated carbon (AC) was treated by applying temperature to AC in air atmosphere, and nitrogen doping by heating AC in ammonium hydroxide solution. Raman spectra and BET analysis indicated that the treated samples exhibited more defects and higher surface area. Incorporation of nitrogen in catalyst structure was detected by CHN analysis and observed by elemental mapping. Low contents of Fe and Co nanoparticles were deposited by two procedures on AC and N-AC after treatment. Elemental mapping and TEM images indicated the homogeneous deposition of metallic nanoparticles on carbonaceous substrates. The synthesized electrocatalysts revealed different activities to ORR in alkaline electrolyte. The performance of electrocatalysts was evaluated by cyclic voltammetry (CV), linear sweep voltammetry (LSV) and chronoamperometry for short-term and long-term ORR study. Long-term activity of FeCo/N-AC430 towards ORR showed better durability compared to Pt/C in alkaline electrolyte. coredata.dc:description: Sluggish oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) is a rate-limiting step in some electrochemical devices such as fuel cells. Thus, the synthesis and development of high performance, inexpensive and durable catalysts for ORR is a necessity. Metallic nanostructures decorated heteroatoms-doped carbons have been recognized as excellent catalysts in energy applications. However, nitrogen-doped partially oxidized three-dimensional carbonaceous supports were seldom studied for ORR. Herein, the synthesis of low Fe-Co bimetallic contents deposited on three-dimensional (3D) activated carbon (AC) is reported as an efficient and cost-effective catalyst for ORR in alkaline electrolyte. In the present work, AC was thermally treated by direct heat in air at 430 °C to enhance its electrochemical activity through increasing structure deficiency. AC and nitrogen doped AC (N-AC) were used to synthesize Fe-Co/AC and Fe-Co/N-AC. In both Fe-Co/AC and Fe-Co/N-AC, low amounts of non-precious Fe and Co nanoparticles were deposited on carbonaceous substrates. The air oxidation process, for partially oxidation of carbon structure and catalyst post treatment, was used for introducing defects to the catalyst structure. The performance of synthesized samples was evaluated by ORR process in alkaline medium.
coredata.dc:title: 3D nitrogen-doped carbon supported non-precious metals electrocatalyst for oxygen reduction reaction
